    "summary": "The domestication of the water buffalo (Bubalus bubalis) took place in the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia, with genetic and archaeological evidence pointing to origins in the Indus Valley region and southern China around 7000–6000 BCE. Wild water buffalo, known as arni, were large, formidable animals that required sustained effort to bring under human management, suggesting that domestication was a gradual process driven by the agricultural communities of the period.\n\nDomesticated water buffalo became one of the most important draft animals in Asian agriculture, capable of plowing waterlogged paddy fields that oxen could not manage effectively. Their milk, hide, and dung for fuel provided additional resources, making them central to the agrarian economies of South and Southeast Asia for millennia.",
